<br>
Back to the point.  IN a world (Earth 2002) where we can't even reliably decide how long ago stuctures were built, or who build 'em ... it is indeed contemplation of a &quot;mystery&quot; to hypothesize on the method of their construction.<br>
<br>
Being in a slightly less whimsical mood than in previous posts, I'd like to say that my subtle suggestion that the use of some kind of &quot;anti-gravity device&quot; is for the most part, only in jest.  (Really, it really is ... I know NOZING about any anti-gravity technologies, NOZING!)<br>
<br>
I guess my commentary would have to be, as I was suggesting in the previous posts, that it is not outside of the scope of what we understand to be possible, (again, as archwriter suggested, although I still read him to be dismissive to the conversation at large), that human will and human intention alone is sufficient to explain who built the Pyramids.  <br>
<br>
BUT, that being said, any other explanation, UNTIL WE KNOW FOR CERTAIN, at least deserves the right to be examined.  One of the problems in &quot;modern science&quot; (sic) is that there are elements in our society that wish to turn it into the New Religion, with assumptions and restrictions as dogmatic (if not moreso) and more disturbing in their implications than any religion ever known.<br>
<br>
