</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/utrinityharmony.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Trinity Harmony</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/26/02 11:11:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/funexplainedmysteriesfrm39.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=47.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.boomspeed.com/geofon/ezboard3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Back to the pyramids</span><hr size=1> <br>
Graham Hancock wrote several books regarding the Egyptians and the pyramids. Fingerprints of the Gods (read this one first), Keeper of Genesis and Heaven's Mirror. <br>
<br>
While he does look in-depth at the pyramids, where they are located and so on, he doesn't tell you who did build them but rather who didn't. His main arguement is that the Sphinx's original head was that of a lion, and that if you follow the star charts, Leo was in ascendency in the east (ie the sun rose through it. At the moment it is Aquarius, hence the &quot;dawning of the age of aquarius&quot;), this would place the sphinx, who is looking directly at the constellation at around 10,500 to 12,500 yearrs ago. Now I haven't explained all the reasoning behind this, too long and compliacted. There is also the aging of the Sphinx by water, there is water erosion patterns on it. Now the Sphinx is believed to be older than the pyramids, fine. So let's move on to them. <br>
<br>
Building methods change all over the world, and it really is a matter of perception. We can't imagine how the pyramids were built because we don't think like the people who built them. The idea of having thousands of slaves to pull tons of rock is great, but how do you do it?<br>
1. what do you use to pull? is there rope strong enough? <br>
2. where slopes of sand used to haul the stones up, building long ramps. great idea, but to get the stones at the very highest point would require a ramp over 3 kms long (if you don't exceed an incline of 30 degrees) [I haven't worked this out, but I remember having this debate with someone else and we worked it out ~ so it might be inaccurate due to my memeory!) <br>
3. how do you get the precision? <br>
4. is is so hard to believe that there could be civilisations that were just as intelligent, but moved in a totally different direction, before us? Look back at this past century and see what has been done in 100 years! Aristotle came up with some brilliant mathematical formulae, that were never known about, until a copy of his works was found in the 20th century. Some of his ideas were at least 500 years before anyone else thought of them. Humans are more ingenious that we remember to be.<br>
<br>
So basically me view on the whole thing is this: the pyramids are older than we think. Humans built them, and we haven't discovered how yet, doesn't mean we won't. There is more, but this post is getting way too long now...  <p><html>
<img src="http://www.boomspeed.com/geofon/frog.gif">
