ptians and the ancient builders in Peru, Yucatan, and Asia, with only primitive tools, raised and set in place blocks of stone weighing many tons.” <br>
<br>
I'm fairly sure that the builder of the Coral Castle was telling the truth there, but he never bothered to tell anyone what those secrets were. He worked alone, and only when he was sure nobody was watching. He moved the blocks by truck, but nobody saw him placing blocks on the trucks, or taking them off. Interestingly enough, there was a short piece on the Art Bell show about the supposed use of magnetics. <br>
<br>
There's a picture here: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.artbell.com/graphics22.html">www.artbell.com/graphics22.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
What does that look like it could do? Could it generate a magnetic field strong enough to lift a 28-ton block of coral?<br>
<br>
Some other interesting tidbits (I'm reluctant to call them &quot;facts&quot;):<br>
A 10th century Arab historian, Abul Hasan Ali Al-Masudi, said the stone blocks used in the Egyptian pyramids were struck with a metal rod and levitated along a path lined with metal poles.<br>
<br>
A group of teenagers claimed to have seen Edward move his blocks of coral by placing his hand on them and singing to them.<br>
<br>
And this:<br>
&quot;In almost every culture where megaliths exist, a legend also exists that the huge stones were moved by acoustic means - either by the chanted spells of magicians, by song (as Coral Castle), by striking with a magic wand or rod (to produce acoustic resonance), or by trumpets, gongs, lyres, cymbals or whistles.&quot; (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.wordmax.com/gallery432/432ston2.htm">www.wordmax.com/gallery432/432ston2.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> - very bottom of the page)<br>
<br>
Magnetics, or acoustics, or both?<br>
Scientists today can levitate objects using either, but nothing even approaching multi-ton blocks of coral or limestone (I've only seen acoustic levitation used on droplets of water). I'd love to see some more theories on this.<br>
<br>
<br>
